L.A. show-goers, Liv Marsico is a familiar face, even if she's behind a drum kit most of the time. Her resumé is stacked; it boasts her percussion duties for several local bands, including Stone Darling, and, most recently, drumming in Gothic Tropic and providing additional vocals for Tapioca & the Flea. As Liphemra, she has finally stepped out on her own. Drawing the name from the concept of "ephemera," Marsico's solo project is an appropriate amalgam of mysteriously ambient swirls with songs like the haunting yet pulsating "Young." Although electronic-based, the multi-instrumentalist in her also embodies elements of gothic, psychedelic rock and jazz for a textured cushion underneath her bright vocals. Liphemra's experimental direction isn't too shocking considering her past rhythmic explorations with others, but it's certainly an enticing listen." - Seraphina Lotkhamnga, Buzzbands.LA

When rock 'n’ roll meets the free soul and freedom is not something you search for but something you become.

The two-piece indie rock band is fronted by vocalist and drummer Sara Haile-Mariam and rooted in the ferocious fretwork of guitarist Mike Sutjipto.

Founded in 2013 after meeting on Craigslist, the duo immediately hit it off as songwriters and collaborators. They explored music as an acoustic act performing in the DC area. Deciding to expand, they came across a drummer without a drum set who wanted to audition. The pair picked up Mike’s high school drum set from his childhood home, and when that drummer never showed up, Sara stepped in and learned to play the drums while holding it down as the group’s lyricist and front woman. Mike dove into playing electric guitar, and the group developed a sound with audible heart - awake, and infused with magic.
